8. Endpoint Security for Enterprise

Enterprise, Enterprise-grade and Objectives

The term "Enterprise" refers to a large and industrious organization in that the scope, complications, and risks associated with its mission require a systematic approach to achieve success. In capitalist economic systems enterprises are reference to large for-profit organizations. Enterprises, by definition, take on risks, financially or otherwise, for rewards in future. Therefore enterprises have different needs from small businesses and individuals, and the products and services that target and are catered to large enterprises have to be business-appropriate to their specific needs.

If you are looking at various categories of products and services you may run into marketing terms such as "enterprise-grade" or "enterprise class". There is no formal or standard definition of "enterprise-grade" or "enterprise-class" (the same can be said about the term "military-grade" as another example). As IT technicians and system administrators, it is up to you to look beyond marketing jargon and terms to determine what makes a particular product or service suitable for your enterprise.

However, there are underlying properties that are desired by large organizations in general. The ultimate goal is to better meet organizational mission objectives and to protect the business mission by reducing risks to the CIA at strategic and tactical levels. For information security policies to be effective in reducing risks, policies must be enforced. To enforce policies, various tools and methods are employed. Technical enforcement of policies is preferred when possible, due to advantages such as preventing human errors and creating friction and resistance to discourage circumvention. However, it is not always possible to implement technical or technological enforcement, due to real-world limitations, such as costs. Some examples of enforcement include:

  • Physical Controls
    • Security guards and staff
    • RFID and other types of ID badges
    • Biometric scanners (Fingerprint, iris scan, hand geometry, etc.)
    • lock and chains, fences and cages, mantraps
    • All requiring logging, monitoring and auditing of physical access
      • enforced technologically, for example, RFID access logs, camera recording, etc.
      • Enforced by policy, for example using logbooks (manually fill in a form or a row in a logbook whenever anyone enters a room)
    • Authentication
    • Encryption
    • Workload Separation
    • Agent-based or agent-less security tools
    • Creating robust service
      • reducing risk of failure by reducing likelihood or impact using:
        • redundancy
        • failover
        • recover
        • continuity plans
        • Reliable hardware solutions to minimize downtime and speed up recover

IT-Centric Enterprise Hardware

There are classes of hardware and systems that are specifically designed to run in a large enterprise environment. While enterprises find this class of equipment cost-effective, individuals and small businesses may find the costs to be quite high. The high costs are not always due to initial investment but also relate to the level of skill required to operate and manage these systems. However, commodity hardware and technological advances have made many of the (formerly) enterprise-grade solutions trickle down into the hands of individuals and smaller organizations.

Examples of some of these enterprise hardware include:

  • Mainframes, Servers, & Storage
  • Accessories and Appliances
    • Monitor, keyboard, mouse, local printers, local scanners, etc…
  • Workstations (client systems)
    • Laptops, Desktops, Workstations
  • Mobile devices
    • cell phones and tablets, Smartwatches, etc.
  • IoT Devices
    • IP Phones, Cameras, network printers, …

Enterprise vs Consumer Hardware

Enterprise hardware is generally built to meet specific targets for the CIA. For example:

  • Hardware made from higher-quality components
    • may carry longer warranty, have higher levels of support, or carry contractual SLA (Service Level Agreements)
  • Hardware serviceability
    • built-in monitoring, diagnostics, and reporting implemented in hardware/software
    • Hardware designed to be easy to repair or replace failed components
    • All to facilitate higher availability and minimize downtime
  • Provide individual or federated management capabilities (proprietary and commodity technologies)
  • Built-in redundancies and failover capabilities
  • Hardware error checking and error correction

As an example, we can look at the typical features of ISS (Industry Standard Server) features:

  • Inventory Management with Built-in QR-Code, RFID, Asset Tagss and other traceability features
  • Integrated Management computer (remote access to hardware for provisioning and monitoring)
  • Case Intrusion Detection
  • Hardware Security Modules such as TPM
  • Radiation Hardened Processor Sockets
  • ECC Memory
  • Redundant Fans and power supplies
  • Hot-swappable fans and power supplies
  • Hot-pluggable storage devices (hard drives or SSDs)
  • Hardware RAID controller
  • Extensible support for IO:
    • NICs for various purposes and speeds
    • HBA (host bus adapter)
    • Accelerators (GPU, FPGA, and other specialized hardware)
    • HSM (Hardware Security Modules)
  • Processor, Platform, and Firmware security and enterprise-oriented features (not available on typical consumer platforms)
    • Secure Boot and Firmware Protection (for example with ability to add or remove trusted keys, password protection, and other security features, Boot Guard)
    • Intel Software Guard Extension (SGX), AMD Secure Encrypted Virtualization (SEV)
    • Data Execution Prevention (DEP)
    • Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)
    • Memory Protection Extensions (MPX)
    • Intel Virtualization Technology (VT-x) and AMD-V

Industry Terminology and Quick Background Information

Memory Types

ECC (Error Correction Code)

Memory bits in computers can sometimes flip due to reasons ranging from hardware failure to various forms of interference to cosmic rays. The more memory a system has and uses, the higher the chances of single or multi-bits being flipped, due to laws of probability, and physics (due to the simple fact that more memory DIMMs have a larger physical presence, and therefore higher chances of interacting with the environment and universe).

Typical methods of combatting memory errors to protect the integrity of data is to equip memory DIMMs with additional hardware to detect and correct up to "n-bits" of errors. The rate of detection and number of correctable bits varies depending on technology and manufacturer. The system platform (the processor and system board) must be compatible and dictate the type and level of error correction and detection.

For more information see: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Error_correction_code.

RDIMM and LRDIMM

In some hardware architectures, the memory controller has to bear the electrical load of the memory DIMMs installed in the system (memory DIMMs need power and signalling also consumes power). In a smaller system that only has a few memory DIMMs this may not be an issue, but in a server that can support dozens to tens of DIMMs per memory controller the electrical load becomes a problem.

RDIMM (Registered DIMM) and LRDIMM (Load Reduced DIMM) are used to effectively offload electrical load from the memory controller by either adding a register or a buffer. In simple terms:

  • RDIMMs use a register to offload Commands and Address communication buses while the data bus is still driven by the memory controller.
  • LRDIMM use a buffer to offload data, commands, and address busses from the memory controller. Either way, the effect is the ability to install more physical memory per processor socket in a system, in some ISS systems reaching multi-terra-bytes of supported memory per server.

RDIMM and LRDIMM typically come with ECC capability included, because there is little reason to not include ECC where RDIMM and LRDIMM are used.

For more information on UDIMM, RDIMM, and LRDIMM see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Registered_memory.

Hot-swap vs Hot-Plug Terminology

To reduce downtime and increase availability, many vendors build hot-plug and hot-swap capabilities into their hardware. There is a difference between these two terms, so if you even want to work on any system that takes advantage of these capabilities, please read the documentation carefully to spot the difference. Some vendors employ colour-coding component touch points and levers to distinguish the difference.

  • Hot-Plug: The component can be removed and replaced without the need to power off the system. This does NOT mean that you can just yank the part out, it only means that the electrical and data connections are capable of handling physical connection and disconnection.
    • For example, in a system with redundant power supplies, the power supplies can be hot-plugged (maybe you may need to unplug the power cord from that power supply first). But if you hot-plug the only remaining power supply, or go below the minimum number required configuration to power your device, your device will be powered off
    • Another example is having a hot-plug storage media (HDDs or SSDs), if the OS is using that device and you unplug it, you may have corrupted files or cause a crash in software that was expecting that storage media to still be present
  • Hot-swap means you can hot-plug a device without affecting any functionality.
    • For example, if your system has two redundant power supplies, one of them will be hot-swappable, meaning one of the two can be pulled out and replaced while your system is running without affecting anything.
    • Another example: One out of two hot-pluggable HDDs in RAID1 (Mirroring) configuration can be hot-swappable

Storage

RAID Levels

For more detailed explanations you can also see: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_RAID_levels

Raid stands for Redundant Array of Inexpensive Disks, and is a method of combining multiple block storage devices to increase performance, reliability, or capacity. There are several concepts behind the standard RAID levels that you must be aware of and understand, to be able to select the correct configuration for your objectives. Here is a list of typical standard RAID levels:

  • Raid 0: Data striping (block-level)
    • requires a minimum of two drives
    • splits the blocks into smaller chunks to be stored on multiple physical drives in parallel
    • Increases performance, theoretically linearly with the number of drives
    • Increases logical block storage capacity, increases linearly by the number of drives
    • There is no redundancy or fault tolerance
      • Any drive failure or sector or block corruption results in data loss or loss of the entire logical drive
  • Raid 1: Mirroring
    • Requires a minimum of two drives
    • duplicates all data across every drive
    • Improves availability and integrity
      • in case of drive failure, an exact copy of data remains on surviving drives
    • Does not increase capacity or performance, the total capacity and performance match the single smallest and slowest member drive.
  • RAID 3: byte-level striping + parity drive
    • Minimum requires 3 drives (two striped similar to RAID0 + 1 Disk to store Parity data)
    • Logical drive capacity is equal to the number of drives minus the parity drive
    • Logical Drive performance is up to I/O of one (1) disk
      • Parity requires calculations to be performed on stripes (affects performance depending on implementation)
    • Logical drive can tolerate failure of only one (1) member drive
      • parity and remaining data strip is used to "rebuild" the missing data, or data strips can be used to "rebuild" the parity
  • RAID 5: block-level striping and distributed parity
    • Requires minimum 3 drives
    • Block-level striping of data for increased capacity and performance similar to RAID 0
      • can potentially provide less performance than RAID 0, due to parity calculations that require computation
      • In some systems with dedicated "hardware controllers" performance can be very close to RAID 0 due to hardware acceleration and offloading for fast parity calculations
      • RAID 5 in some systems may be more vulnerable to bit-rot
    • Logical drive capacity is the capacity of all drives minus one (equivalent capacity of one drive is used for parity)
    • logical drive can tolerate failure of only one (1) member drive
  • RAID 6: Double-parity
    • At minimum requires 4 drives
    • Same striping as RAID 5, but with two parity calculations
    • Depending on the implementation, it can store two of the same parity, or calculate two different parity depending on the algorithm used
      • This is used as a mitigation of "bit-rot" problems associated with RAID 5
    • Performance can be on par with RAID 5, given that there are enough hardware resources for fast parity calculations
    • Storage capacity of the logical drive is the number of drives minus two
    • Can tolerate failure of up to two member drives

The most currently used RAID levels are RAID 0, 1, 5 and 6, RAID 2 and 3 are impractical and mostly deprecated in modern systems. When looking at hardware specifications, for example when purchasing a server or storage device, you may have the ability to choose different RAID Controllers that may vary in capabilities, such as the number of supported drives and RAID level capabilities.

Nested or Hybrid RAID

It simply means combining multiple raid levels into a single logical volume. For example, RAID 0+1 means combining RAID 0 volumes into a RAID 1 volume. This example requires at least 4 physical disks.

There are other hybrid combinations such as RAID 1+0, RAID 5+1, etc. They are self-explanatory if you know your RAID levels well enough.

Software RAID vs Hardware RAID

RAID levels can be implemented at the OS and kernel level in software as long as the software has direct block access to a physical storage device hardware (meaning it can get complicated in virtual environments). There are many advantages and disadvantages to using software vs hardware RAID.
Advantages of software RAID include:

  • portability: in case of a catastrophic hardware failure, the storage drives can be moved to another system and as long as the same OS/Software can be installed, the logical software RAID volume can be restored.
    • in comparison, hardware RAID controllers are proprietary. In case of a hardware failure, the same RAID Controller card or a compatible one must be present for the logical volume to be detected and function in a new system
      • as an example cannot pull HDDs from a failed HPE Proliant server using HPE SmartArray and attach to a Dell PowerEdge with PERC controller and expect to get any data out of the logical drive
      • I have moved HDDs with software RAID volumes from a desktop to a server (different system hardware) and was still able to restore all functionality and use the data in the logical volume
        Disadvantage of Software RAID:
  • Reliance on corruptible mutable software (as with all software updates or version changes can cause issues)
  • Challenges and risks of installing OS in a partition that depends on the software or driver that is loaded from the same software RAID volume
    • For example, I have had issues at customer sites where a disk failure on a software RAID 1 using Intel chipset software makes the Windows unbootable, while the only way to fix the volume is by using the Intel software from that Windows installation.
      Advantage of Hardware RAID:
  • All the low level drive and volume operations are offloaded and do not affect the running software or OS. The RAID controller handles drive testing, reporting, failure, and rebuilding without affecting software (customer or user may not even be aware of a failed disk)

Bit-rot

Is a term used to describe when undetectable errors in the stored data occur. Bit-rot usually happens due to probabilistic failures in the storage medium. As an example, most (if not all) HDDs and SSDs are equipped with S.M.A.R.T hardware and firmware to detect and correct errors (using ECC) and identify and avoid bad sectors or cells on the storage medium. However since the storage medium is storing billions of bits, on very rare occasions multiple bits can flip in a way that the checksum remains unchanged (ECC not triggered), therefore making the corruption undetectable.

Depending on the configuration, the probability of bit-rot compounds when additional storage mediums are combined into a single logical drive. While RAID 1 and RAID 6 can help mitigate bit-rot by reducing probability. However, RAID 0 and RAID 5 are vulnerable.

RAID 0 logical drive does not have any redundancies, the data for integrity can be checked at the file system level. Corrupted data will need to be restored from other sources such as backup or snapshot.

RAID 5 is particularly vulnerable to bit-rot because it is impossible to detect corruption at the file system level. The data corruption only becomes apparent during a RAID 5 logical drive rebuild process. The missing data from a failed drive cannot be reconstructed and stored in the new replacement drive when the required correlating data or parity is corrupted. The available remedies are restoring the logical drive and missing data from backups or very expensive data recovery on the failed physical drive member, given that the RAID 5 logical volume has not been changed since the failure (very expensive and very low chance of success in a production server).
